Ekdom! **Physics-Informed LSTM (PI-LSTM)** holo ekta advanced "Hybrid" approach. Traditional LSTM shudhu data-r pattern dekhe (black box), kintu PI-LSTM pichon theke physics-er rules (differential equations) diye model-ke constrain kore.

Tomar **Current System Control**-er kotha mathay rekhe ami ekta killer project idea dichhi:

---

## Project Title: **"Smart-Grid Fault Predictor using Physics-Informed LSTM"**

Ei project-e tumi ekta electrical transmission line ba microgrid-er current flow predict korbe. Normal LSTM ekhane fail kore karon electrical fault-er somoy data khub erratic hoye jay, kintu PI-LSTM physics jane bole sheta handle korte pare.

### ১. Mathematical Foundation (The Physics)

Amra jani ekta transmission line-er current ($i$) ar voltage ($v$) nicher differential equation (RL circuit model) mene chole:


$$L \frac{di}{dt} + Ri = v(t)$$


LSTM prediction korar somoy jodi ei equation follow na kore, tobe amra model-ke "penalty" (Loss) dibo.

### ২. Implementation Steps

* **Data Generation (The Julia/MATLAB Part):** Tumi `DifferentialEquations.jl` ba MATLAB Simulink use kore ekta transmission line-er normal ar faulty condition-er current/voltage data generate koro.
* **The Model (Python Part):** * Input: Last 50 time-steps er current ($i$) ar voltage ($v$).
* Architecture: LSTM Layers followed by a Dense Layer.


* **The Secret Sauce (Physics Loss):** * Loss function-e shudhu Mean Squared Error (MSE) thakbe na.
* Tumi Autograd (`torch.autograd` ba `tf.GradientTape`) use kore LSTM output-er derivative ($di/dt$) nibe.
* Tarpor check korbe $L(di/dt) + Ri - v$ er value koto. Eta joto zero-r kachakachi hobe, model toto bhalo physics shikche.



